<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus longaeva </i>is a long-lived, multistemmed tree that attains nearly 4900 years in age and 12 m in height. Trees are intolerant of shade and grow slowly in low-moisture, high elevations with a growing season of fewer than 50 days. Branches retain needles for as long as 30 years, and the trees have deep, spreading roots. Cone ripening and seed dispersal occur in the fall. Clark’s nutcrackers, other birds, and small mammals disperse and cache seeds. The species’ longevity enables it to bridge long periods between seedling establishments (Ahlenslager 1987). Trees produce dense, resinous wood that is resistant to rot and disease. Mature trees have massive, contorted trunks with mostly dead and gnarled wood. <i>Pinus longaeva </i>is a rare CNPS list 4 plant. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance occurs as scattered subalpine woodlands in Utah and Nevada; it extends into eastern California, where it is the timberline tree of high desert ranges. This woodland alliance endures harsh, dry, high-elevation conditions in California, such as in the White Mountains, with their nutrient-deficient soils and precipitation of less than 40 cm a year, mostly in the form of snow (Thorne et al. 2007). Stands have only <i>Pinus longaeva </i>or are mixed with <i>Pinus flexilis </i>in the overstory. Stands are usually pure, even aged, and open, with canopy cover usually less than 20%. Trees reach their greatest densities on north-facing slopes. Although the understory is sparse, it is usually diverse, with natives including <i>Arenaria kingii, Astragalus kentrophyta, Cryptantha </i>spp., <i>Eriogonum ovalifolium, E. gracilipes, Koeleria macrantha</i> and <i>Linanthus pungens</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
