    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dj). <i>Pinus longaeva</i> ranges from 2620 to 3540 m in elevation in the White Mountains (Lloyd and Mitchell 1973). The most famous stands are in the Schulman Grove in the White Mountain RNA and in the Patriarch Grove, both of which occur in the Ancient Bristlecone Pine Forest. <i>P. longaeva</i> is usually the only conifer present at these locations. Stands at Whippoorwill Flat RNA in the Inyo Mountains are mixed with <i>P. flexilis</i> (Cheng 2004, Taylor 1979).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb, Fd, Ff). Stands clothe the ridges and peaks of the Grapevine, Inyo, Last Chance, and Panamint mountains, including both pure stands and stands mixed with <i>P. flexilis</i> (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus longaeva </i>stands have high recreational and wildlife habitat value: the Ancient Bristlecone Pine Forest, for example, protects nearly 11,735 ha in the White Mountains of Inyo National Forest as a result of the California Wild Heritage Act of 2007. Stands have high-use habitats for mammals and small birds because the stands are a major source for cover and nesting in high elevations (Howard 2004b). 

<i>Pinus longaeva </i>provides the longest continual and some of the most climatically sensitive tree ring chronologies in the world; the best chronologies are obtained from slow-growing pines on harsh sites, such as in the White Mountains. However, stands are vulnerable to fungi, parasites, and insect attacks, including mountain pine beetle infestations. Populations in the White and Inyo mountains are at great risk for blister rust infection and spread because they are close to moderately-high infection centers in the Sierra Nevada (Howard 2004b). </div>
</div>

    

    

